define({"0":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/MC2_About.htm",l:-1,t:"About Drilling Engineering Software",i:0.00125571896981037,a:"Welcome to Drilling Engineering Software  v2.4.15. Drilling Engineering Software gives you a single software platform for designing, planning, and monitoring drilling operations. Drilling Engineering Software allows you to plan nearly every detail of drilling a well, from the trajectory  of the well ..."},"1":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/MC2_SysReqs.htm",l:-1,t:"System requirements",i:0.00184790332949025,a:"The system requirements for Drilling Engineering Software are listed below, including the requirements for processor speed, memory, disk space, graphics card, operating system, screen resolution, and software."},"2":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/MC2_ReleaseNotes.htm",l:-1,t:"Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.15 Release Notes",i:0.00159456484897883,a:"Welcome to Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.15. This version of Drilling Engineering Software contains several new features and enhancements, as well as many bug fixes. For a full list of the updates in v2.4.15, refer to the sections below."},"3":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.15 Knowledge Base",i:0.00306181908240833,a:"In this article About the knowledge base General issues Projects screen Setup screen About the knowledge base The Drilling Engineering Software knowledge base provides you with solutions to known issues and common problems. If we find new issues, we\u0027ll tell you about them and give you solutions. If ..."},"4":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_002.htm",l:-1,t:"Text or buttons are cut off on the screen",i:0.0012627405507036,a:"Text, buttons, or other parts of Drilling Engineering Software are cut off on the screen, even when Drilling Engineering Software is maximized. This problem may occur if your screen resolution is too low. The lowest screen resolution supported by Drilling Engineering Software is 1024 x 768. To change your..."},"5":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_007.htm",l:-1,t:"Drilling Engineering Software freezes after a remote connection",i:0.0012627405507036,a:"When you connect to a remote computer that is running Drilling Engineering Software, the application initially appears to be frozen. The graphs appear on the Home screen for a couple of seconds, then disappear. When you connect to a remote computer, Windows creates a new remote session. When this happens, Windows..."},"6":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_011.htm",l:-1,t:"Hydraulics model crashes at shallow well depths",i:0.0035174554335938,a:"When the well depth is less than 200 ft, the hydraulics model does not function. There is no fluid shown in the diagram for the well schematic, and there are no values shown in the Hydraulics Data indicator. On the Alarms \u003e Hydraulics Model page, the status indicator for the hydraulics model is red. When you restart the hydraulics..."},"7":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_014.htm",l:-1,t:"Imports and exports fail on Windows 7",i:0.00761522861234599,a:"Related Topics Symptom When you attempt to import or export a well, you get error: \"Unable to load one or more of the requested types. Retrieve the Loader Exceptions property for more information.\" Note This knowledge base article only applies to installations of Drilling Engineering Software on ..."},"8":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_016.htm",l:-1,t:"Experiments from imported projects show incorrect results",i:0.00464966266503611,a:"Related Topics Symptom When you import a project file that includes analysis experiments, the experiment results are incorrect or incomplete. Solution Drilling Engineering Software\u0027s analysis models are updated frequently. When you import a project file from a previous version of Drilling ..."},"9":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_003.htm",l:-1,t:"WITS/WITSML source parameters are missing",i:0.00747023273821842,a:"When you try to configure the well parameters on the Setup \u003e Mappings \u003e Parameters tab, some of the WITS or WITSML mnemonics are not listed. This problem usually occurs when the WITS or WITSML mnemonic isn\u0027t configured correctly. Check the settings for the mnemonic on the Setup \u003e DAQ page..."},"10":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_004.htm",l:-1,t:"Sea floor depth error when saving well intervals",i:0.00487512185626162,a:"Related Topics Symptom When you attempt to save your changes to the well configuration, you get the following error: \"Sea floor depth cannot exceed hole depth.\" This error may occur on any time the well configuration is edited, such as on the following pages: Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Equipment ..."},"11":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_005.htm",l:-1,t:"Intermittent connectivity with WITS/WITSML",i:0.00781656386256954,a:"Drilling Engineering Software intermittently loses connection with the WITS or WITSML server. On the Alarms \u003e DAQ page, the status for the WITS or WITSML channel changes from green to red. Drilling Engineering Software assumes incoming data is updated every five seconds..."},"12":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/KB/KB_009.htm",l:-1,t:"Piping not included in surface pressure loss calculations",i:0.00893898045285072,a:"When you customize the surface piping on the Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Piping and Instrumentation tab, the changes are not reflected in the surface pressure loss calculations for a hydraulics snapshot analysis. When you select a pre-defined rig size on the Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Equipment Configuration tab..."},"13":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/MC2_Support.htm",l:-1,t:"Reporting problems",i:0.00377853283809061,a:"Before you submit a support ticket, it\u0027s a good idea to check for known issues and solutions. The knowledge base is included in the Drilling Engineering Software user guide and contains workarounds for several known issues."},"14":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Drilling Engineering Software Video Library",i:0.00837045959706843,a:"In this article Project videos Setup videos Planning videos Dashboards videos Warning You must be signed into Microsoft with your Weatherford log-in to view the videos below. If the videos do not automatically load, click the Sign In link to sign into your account. If the sign-in window does not ..."},"15":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Projects.htm",l:-1,t:"Projects videos",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Projects videos Projects: Creating a new project (3:49) Created for Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.14 Projects: Reprocessing data from WITSML (3:30) Created for OneSync® v2.1.3"},"16":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Projects_Add.htm",l:-1,t:"Projects: Creating a new project",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you about the different ways to create a new project in Drilling Engineering Software. You can create a blank project from scratch, or you can copy the configuration of an existing well. (3:49) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to ..."},"17":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Projects_Reprocess_WITSML.htm",l:-1,t:"Projects: Reprocessing data from WITSML",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you how to reprocess historical data from a WITSML channel. Reprocessing data treats historical data as if it had been acquired in real-time, allowing you to correct errors in the well configuration, run new calculations, and include additional models. (3:30) Warning ..."},"18":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup videos",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Setup: Entering rig information (1:59) Created for Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.15 Setup: Entering equipment specifications (3:41) Created for Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.15 Setup: Importing wellpath data from a file (2:46) Created for Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.15 Setup: ..."},"19":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_RIG_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Entering rig information",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you how to enter the basic information about the surface equipment on the rig. The information about the surface equipment is used to determine the starting depth of well and the hanger depth for casing sections. (1:59) Warning This video is hosted on an internal ..."},"20":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_RIG_Specs.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Entering equipment specifications",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Setup: Entering equipment specifications This video tutorial will teach you how to enter the specifications for the equipment on the rig, such as the derrick, the pumps, and other equipment. (3:41) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to external viewers."},"21":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_TRJ_ImportFile.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Importing wellpath data from a file",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Setup: Importing wellpath data from a file This video tutorial will teach you how to import wellpath data from a CSV file. (2:46) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to external viewers."},"22":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_INT_Define.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Defining well intervals",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Setup: Defining well intervals This video tutorial will teach you how to define the geometry of the casing sections and open hole sections along the trajectory of the well. (3:24) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to external viewers."},"23":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_TMP_Add.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Adding a temperature profile",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Setup: Adding a temperature profile This video tutorial will teach you how to add a temperature profile to define the distribution of temperatures throughout the well. (1:35) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to external viewers."},"24":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_FLD_Add.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Adding drilling muds",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you how to add a drilling mud to a well. The mud properties are used to calculate the real-time hydraulics. They are also used for analyses on the Planning screen. (2:37) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to external viewers."},"25":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_WS_Add.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Building a work string",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Setup: Building a work string This video tutorial will teach you how to create a new work string, how to add tools to the work string, and how to change the active work string. (4:17) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to external viewers."},"26":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_CAT_Tools_Add.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Adding custom tools",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Custom catalogs allow you to create custom work string tools that do not exist in the default Drilling Engineering Software catalog. This video tutorial will teach you how to add a custom tool catalog, create a custom tool, and add it to a work string. (2:29) Warning This video is hosted on an ..."},"27":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Setup_DAQ_WML_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup: Adding WITSML channels",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Setup: Adding WITSML channels This video tutorial will teach you how to configure Drilling Engineering Software to receive real-time data from a WITSML log. (2:07) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to external viewers."},"28":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Plan.htm",l:-1,t:"Planning videos",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Planning: Running a torque and drag analysis (3:24) Created for Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.15 Planning: Running a hydraulics snapshot analysis (3:53) Created for Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.15 Planning: Running a hydraulics parametric analysis (3:39) Created for Drilling Engineering ..."},"29":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Plan_AMTD_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Planning: Running a torque and drag analysis",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you how to configure a torque and drag analysis, view the results, and create a report. Torque and drag analysis predicts the torque \u0026 drag forces generated by the drillstring during various wellbore operations. It calculates the forces, torques, and stresses that act ..."},"30":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Plan_AHS_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Planning: Running a hydraulics snapshot analysis",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you how to configure a hydraulics snapshot analysis, view the results, and create a report. A snapshot analysis gives you a quick summary of the fluid\u0027s predicted behavior in the wellbore, based on a single value for each operating parameter. It calculates several ..."},"31":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Plan_AHP_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Planning: Running a hydraulics parametric analysis",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you how to configure hydraulics parametric analysis, view the results, and create a report. Hydraulics parametric analysis examines the impact of flow rate, top drive speed, and other operating parameters on ECD and hole cleaning. The analysis allows you to include ..."},"32":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Plan_AHT_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Planning: Running a hydraulics surge and swab analysis",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you how to configure a surge and swab analysis, view the results, and create a report. Swab and surge analysis predicts the swab and surge effects on pressure when running the bit in or out of the well, for open or closed systems. You can also use the analysis to ..."},"33":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_Plan_AHD_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Planning: Running a hydraulics displacement analysis",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"This video tutorial will teach you how to configure a hydraulics displacement analysis, view the results, and create a report. A displacement analysis simulates the movement of fluids through the wellbore during drilling or cementing operations. You can create a fluid train with multiple fluids, ..."},"34":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_DASH.htm",l:-1,t:"Dashboards videos",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Dashboards videos Dashboards: Introduction to dashboards (3:26) Created for Drilling Engineering Software v2.4.14"},"35":{y:0,u:"../Content/General/Videos/VID_DASH_Intro.htm",l:-1,t:"Dashboards: Introduction to dashboards",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"Dashboards: Introduction to dashboards This video tutorial will teach you how to create and customize a dashboard. Dashboards are fully customizable grids that contain gauges, graphs, and indicators. (3:26) Warning This video is hosted on an internal server and is not available to external viewers."},"36":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/QS_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Getting Started",i:0.00197685637730326,a:"This section guides you through the basic steps for setting up Drilling Engineering Software. After you have completed the steps in this guide, you\u0027ll be ready to create dashboards to monitor incoming data and run planning, geomechanics, mechanics, and hydraulics analyses."},"37":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Project/QS_PROJ_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Start a project",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"The first step for using Drilling Engineering Software is to start a new project. When you start a new job, you\u0027ll need to create a well and choose the unit system for the new well. Create a well. When you create a well, you\u0027ll need to enter basic details about the job, such as the well location, ..."},"38":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Project/QS_PROJ_NewWell.htm",l:-1,t:"Adding a new well",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"In the Drilling Engineering Software application suite, all of the data related to a job is stored with the well. This includes job information, the rig configuration, well data, fluid properties, and other data. Wells are managed from the File screen in Drilling Engineering Software. You can create, export, and import wells from this screen."},"39":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Project/QS_PROJ_AssignUnits.htm",l:-1,t:"Choosing a unit system",i:0.00121306948781921,a:"Next, you\u0027ll need to assign a unit system to the well. The Setup \u003e Units page contains the settings for the measurement units used throughout Drilling Engineering Software. It shows the available unit systems, as well as the measurement units and decimal places used for each type of unit. The tabs on the right side..."},"40":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Rig/QS_RIG_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Update rig equipment",i:0.00147084735739543,a:"The next step is to add information about the surface equipment for the well in the Setup \u003e Surface Equipment section. The  Surface Equipment section contains information about the rig, such as the type of rig, the elevation of the rig, and the equipment on the rig. There are four basic steps for ..."},"41":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Rig/QS_RIG_SelectEquip.htm",l:-1,t:"Configuring rig equipment",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"The Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Equipment Configuration tab allows you to select the equipment on the rig, as well as the size and type of rig. The rig equipment available on the Equipment Configuration tab includes blowout preventers, auxiliary pumps, and RCDs."},"42":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Rig/QS_RIG_EnterElev.htm",l:-1,t:"Entering rig elevations",i:0.00138072995748079,a:"The Well View pane on the Setup \u003eSurface Equipment \u003e Equipment Configuration tab shows a diagram that illustrates the kelly bushing, ground level, and water depth of the rig. The diagram shown depends on the type of rig selected in the Rig Type field."},"43":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Rig/QS_RIG_RigLimits.htm",l:-1,t:"Entering rig limits",i:0.00123020278542556,a:"The specifications for the derrick, such as the hoisting capacity and torque rating, are used to calculate tension limits and torque limits for torque and drag calculations. To enter the rig limits: 1. Go to the Piping and Instrumentation tab on the Setup \u003e Surface Equipment page. 2. Select the derrick in the rig schematic..."},"44":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Rig/QS_RIG_ActivatePumps.htm",l:-1,t:"Activating additional pumps",i:0.00148156636800797,a:"The first pump is the only pump that is activated by default. If there are additional pumps on the rig, each additional pump must be activated in order to be used in Drilling Engineering Software\u0027s calculations. On the Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Piping and Instrumentation tab, you can change the pump state..."},"45":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/DAQ/QS_DAQ_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Set up incoming data",i:0.00220805905135622,a:"After you\u0027ve updated the rig equipment created the well, you\u0027ll need to configure the incoming data. There are three basic steps for configuring incoming data: Set up WITS data. Incoming WITS data is configured on the Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITS page.  See \"Setting up WITS data\". Set up WITSML data. Incoming ..."},"46":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/DAQ/QS_DAQ_WITS.htm",l:-1,t:"Setting up WITS data",i:0.00120939815040251,a:"WITS is a two-way communication system used for sending and receiving drilling data. WITS data can be sent across the network through a TCP/IP connection. The Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITS page is used to configure Drilling Engineering Software to send and receive WITS data."},"47":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/DAQ/QS_DAQ_WITSML.htm",l:-1,t:"Setting up WITSML data",i:0.00145710693564023,a:"WITSML is the petroleum industry\u0027s standard for sharing drilling and completions data. Using WITSML allows you to easily send and receive real-time data, without worrying about incompatible data formats and software.The Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITSML page is used to configure Drilling Engineering Software to receive WITSML data."},"48":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/DAQ/QS_DAQ_WellParams.htm",l:-1,t:"Defining well parameters",i:0.00128017208904185,a:"Well parameters such as bit depth, well depth, ROP, and hookload are used by Drilling Engineering Software to create persistent curves for graphs and gauges. If you lose connection with the WITS or WITSML server, gauges and graphs that are mapped to well parameter curves will remain intact."},"49":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Well_Data/QS_WD_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Add well data",i:0.00282025344451033,a:"The next step is to add data about the well, such as the well trajectory, formation characteristics, and well intervals.  All of the data needed to describe the well can be entered on the Setup \u003e  Wells section. Before receiving data or running an analysis, you\u0027ll need to add the data listed below. ..."},"50":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Well_Data/QS_WD_TRJ.htm",l:-1,t:"Importing wellpath data",i:0.00128017208904185,a:"The next step is to add the wellpath information. The Setup \u003e Well Data \u003e Wellpath tab contains the wellpath data for the planned well trajectory and real-time surveys. The drop-down menu at the bottom of the screen allows you to switch between the trajectory data and the survey data..."},"51":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Well_Data/QS_WD_FRM.htm",l:-1,t:"Describing the formation",i:0.00162561645386909,a:"The next step is to describe the wellbore formation. The Setup \u003e Well Data \u003e Formations tab contains the geological and geophysical characteristics of the formation layers in the wellbore. These properties include porosity, permeability, pore pressure, and fracture pressure. Formation layers are indexed..."},"52":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Well_Data/QS_WD_INT.htm",l:-1,t:"Creating wellbore intervals",i:0.00196463465062395,a:"The next step is to add the wellbore intervals. The Well Intervals tab on the Setup \u003e Well Data page is used to define the geometry of the hole sections along the trajectory of the well. Casing sections are listed in the top portion of the Well Intervals tab, and open hole sections are listed at the bottom. The Well View..."},"53":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Run_Data/QS_RUN_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Add run data",i:0.00393997555264818,a:"The next step is to create dashboards to monitor incoming data and run planning, geomechanics, mechanics, and hydraulics analyses."},"54":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Run_Data/QS_RUN_DrillString.htm",l:-1,t:"Building a work string",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"The next step is to build the drillstring that you will be using in the well. The Setup \u003e Work String page is used to build drillstrings and customize drillstring components. In Drilling Engineering Software, the drillstring includes the BHA and drillstring, from the bit to the surface."},"55":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Run_Data/QS_RUN_Fluid.htm",l:-1,t:"Adding fluids",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"The next step is to define drilling and cementing fluids. The Setup \u003e Fluid Properties page contains the properties for the muds, cements, and underbalanced fluids that will be used during drilling and cementing operations. When you create a new mud, the basic fluid..."},"56":{y:0,u:"../Content/QuickStart/Run_Data/QS_RUN_PumpFluid.htm",l:-1,t:"Setting pump fluids",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"The Fluids utility allows you to set the initial fluid, change the current pump fluid, and offset the mud\u0027s pumping time. The current pump fluid determines which drilling fluid is being pumped into the wellbore. The initial fluid is the fluid that is in the wellbore when the job begins. The hydraulics model assumes that the initial fluid..."},"57":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/GUI_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Tour of the Drilling Engineering Software interface",i:0.00364698186119499,a:"Drilling Engineering Software has four major areas: The banner at the top of the screen shows warnings, errors, and system notifications. It also allows you to switch application modes, start data acquisition, and view the current rig activity. In Playback mode, it allows you to control the playback ..."},"58":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/GUI_Banner.htm",l:-1,t:"Main banner",i:0.0227021516571576,a:"The banner at the top of the screen shows warnings, errors, and system notifications. It also allows you to switch application modes, start data acquisition, and view the current rig activity. In Playback mode, it allows you to control the playback speed. The Application Modes area, on the left side of the banner, shows the current application mode..."},"59":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/GUI_NavPane.htm",l:-1,t:"Navigation pane",i:0.0023450246802735,a:"The Navigation pane is used to navigate between the different screens and pages in Drilling Engineering Software. There are three main areas in the Navigation pane: The main menu, located on the left side of the Navigation pane, is used to navigate between the primary screens in Drilling Engineering Software. The secondary navigation pane, located on the right side ..."},"60":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/GUI_WellView.htm",l:-1,t:"Well View pane",i:0.00795773644580315,a:"The Well View pane, on the right side of the screen, is visible from any screen in . It includes a visualization of the well and relevant information about the well, such as casing depths and sizes, mud weight, pressure, and bit position..."},"61":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Utilities",i:0.00131170296886336,a:"The Utilities toolbar contains useful utilities that allow you to change fluids, view incoming data, record videos, capture screenshots, and open the Drilling Engineering Software user guide. These utilities can be used from any screen throughout Drilling Engineering Software."},"62":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Mud.htm",l:-1,t:"Mud utility",i:0.022982401714141,a:"The Mud utility allows you to set the initial fluid, change the current pump fluid, and offset the mud\u0027s pumping time. The current pump fluid determines which drilling fluid is being pumped into the wellbore. There are three primary tasks for pump fluids: Set the initial pump fluid. After you create the drilling fluids..."},"63":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Ind_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Indicators utility",i:0.00369271354032558,a:"The Indicators View utility contains indicators and tools that allow you to view incoming data from hydraulics calculations, calculated values, well parameters, WITSML, and WITS. You can also use the Indicators utility to open custom panels and edit bit runs. Drilling Engineering Software includes ..."},"64":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Ind_Params.htm",l:-1,t:"Parameters indicator",i:0.00418744486159176,a:"The Parameters window shows the current values for the well parameters, defined on the Setup \u003e Mappings \u003e Parameters page. To open the Parameters window, click on the Guides utility, then click on Indicators View and select the Parameters option..."},"65":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Ind_DAQ.htm",l:-1,t:"Data acquisition indicators",i:0.0146775096807083,a:"The indicators under the DAQ menu in the Utilities toolbar allow to view incoming data configured in the Setup \u003e DAQ section. This includes data from WITS channels, WITSML logs, and OPC UA channels. To view the DAQ indicators, click on the Guides utility, then click on Indicators View."},"66":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Ind_BitRuns.htm",l:-1,t:"Bit runs",i:0.0013492609620073,a:"The Bit Runs window allows you to create and manage bit runs. Defining the bit runs for a job gives you another way to filter historical data on the Dashboards screen. To open the Bit Runs window, click on the Guides utility, then click on Indicators View and select the Bit Runs option."},"67":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Ind_CustPanels.htm",l:-1,t:"Custom panels",i:0.00591036474180896,a:"Custom panels are standalone windows that can be re-sized and moved anywhere on your screen. Custom panels contain gauges, which give you a quick visual indication of the status for any parameters, calculated value, or WITS/WITSML curve. The gauges in a custom panel function the same way as gauges in a dashboard."},"68":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Record.htm",l:-1,t:"Capture Video utility",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"The Record Video utility allows you to record a video of Drilling Engineering Software. Recordings can be a useful for recording real-time data when problems are encountered downhole. They can also be used for training rig personnel, client presentations, and post-well reviews."},"69":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Screen.htm",l:-1,t:"Capture Screen utility",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"The Screen Capture utility allows you to take a screenshot of Drilling Engineering Software. Screen captures can be useful for training rig personnel, client presentations, and post-well reviews. The Screen Capture utility takes a screenshot of your entire screen. If you have multiple monitors, all of your screens..."},"70":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Utilities/UTIL_Tutorial.htm",l:-1,t:"Tutorial Help utility",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"The Tutorial utility opens the user guide for Drilling Engineering Software. There are several options listed under the Tutorial utility, each of which opens a specific topic in the user guide. You can also open the user guide by pressing the F1 key when you are using Drilling Engineering Software."},"71":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Options/OPT_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Display options",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"On the Global Settings \u003e System Preferences page, you can customize the Drilling Engineering Software interface. There are several ways to customize the Drilling Engineering Software interface, such as well schemes, trajectory views, color schemes, graph line styles, and graph display settings."},"72":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Options/OPT_Well.htm",l:-1,t:"Well schemes",i:0.00576918829748302,a:"Well schemes control the visualization of the well in the Well View pane, as well as the information that is displayed. There are three default well schemes included in Drilling Engineering Software: Sketch, Diagram, and Engineering. The Sketch well scheme shows only basic illustrations of the well intervals and drillstring..."},"73":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Options/OPT_Traj.htm",l:-1,t:"Trajectory views",i:0.00148261863681407,a:"Trajectory views show a visual representation of the current wellbore trajectory in the Well View pane. Trajectory views include information about casing depths and sizes, the current bit position, standpipe pressure, surface backpressure, bottomhole pressure, and bottomhole ECD."},"74":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Options/OPT_Color.htm",l:-1,t:"Color schemes",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"On the Global Settings \u003e System Preferences \u003e Color Schemes tab, you can change the current color scheme. Color schemes are themes that control the appearance of the Drilling Engineering Software interface. Each color scheme uses a custom set of colors and icons."},"75":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Options/OPT_GraphStyles.htm",l:-1,t:"Graph line styles",i:0.0126917815286585,a:"On the Global Settings \u003e System Preferences \u003e Graph Line Styles tab, you can customize and create graph line styles. Graph line styles control the default appearance of the curves in the graphs on the Dashboards screen. Before you create any custom dashboards, you can create custom line styles for different types of curves. For example..."},"76":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Options/OPT_InterfaceSettings.htm",l:-1,t:"Interface settings",i:0.012377027373173,a:"Interface settings control the legends, spacing, and abbreviations in the graphs throughout Drilling Engineering Software. You can customize these settings on the Global Settings \u003e System Preferences \u003e Interface Settings tab. The interface settings include: Legends Are Visible - When this option is selected, graph legends..."},"77":{y:0,u:"../Content/Reports/RPT_Reports_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Reports",i:0.00443926192770487,a:"In the Reports \u003e Reports section, you can create customizable reports that contain a detailed summary of the well and the drilling performance on the rig. There are two types of reports: on-demand reports and scheduled reports. Both types of reports can include the same types of information, such as information about rig..."},"78":{y:0,u:"../Content/Reports/RPT_Reports_OnDemand.htm",l:-1,t:"On-demand reports",i:0.00348851439853176,a:"The Reports \u003e Reports \u003e On-Demand page allows you to create an on-demand monitoring report that contains a detailed summary of the well and the drilling performance on the rig. On-demand reports are generated based on the date selected in the Report Date field. The report includes information about rig activities, friction..."},"79":{y:0,u:"../Content/Reports/RPT_Reports_Scheduled.htm",l:-1,t:"Scheduled reports",i:0.0133701655199737,a:"The Reports \u003e Reports \u003e Scheduled page allows you to schedule monitoring reports that contain a detailed summary of the well and the drilling performance on the rig. Scheduled reports can be generated on an hourly, daily, or weekly basis."},"80":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Dashboards/DASH_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Dashboards",i:0.00711729855971627,a:"Dashboards are fully customizable grids that you can add graphs, gauges, indicators, and other items to, using any combination of curves. These items can be added from the Dashboard Editor, which also lists the available curves for Drilling Engineering Software."},"81":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Dashboards/DASH_Gauges.htm",l:-1,t:"Gauges",i:0.0152775597861216,a:"Gauges give you a quick visual indication of the status for any parameter or calculated value. You can add gauges to dashboards on the Home screen, as well as to custom panels. Custom panels are standalone windows that can be re-sized and moved anywhere on your screen."},"82":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Dashboards/DASH_Graphs_Time.htm",l:-1,t:"Time graphs",i:0.0095755981472335,a:"Time and depth graphs plot curve data against either time or measured depth. Time and depth graphs have two axes. The primary axis is the graph index, either time or the measured depth of the well. The data in every track is plotted against the data for the graph index. In vertical graphs, the graph index is on the right side of the..."},"83":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Dashboards/DASH_Graphs_Time_Create.htm",l:-1,t:"Creating time graphs",i:0.00148261863681407,a:"Time and depth graphs plot curve data against either time or measured depth. Time and depth graphs have two axes. The primary axis is the graph index, either time or the measured depth of the well. The data in every track is plotted against the data for the graph index. In vertical graphs, the graph index is on the right side of the..."},"84":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Dashboards/DASH_Graphs_Time_Customize.htm",l:-1,t:"Customizing time graphs",i:0.00432197994496042,a:"Time and depth graphs plot curve data against either time or measured depth. Time and depth graphs have two axes. The primary axis is the graph index, either time or the measured depth of the well. The data in every track is plotted against the data for the graph index. In vertical graphs, the graph index is on the right side of the..."},"85":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Dashboards/DASH_Graphs_Depth.htm",l:-1,t:"Depth graphs",i:0.0116555165310543,a:"Time and depth graphs plot curve data against either time or measured depth. Time and depth graphs have two axes. The primary axis is the graph index, either time or the measured depth of the well. The data in every track is plotted against the data for the graph index. In vertical graphs, the graph index is on the right side of the..."},"86":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Dashboards/DASH_Graphs_Depth_Create.htm",l:-1,t:"Creating depth graphs",i:0.00424748485710499,a:"Time and depth graphs plot curve data against either time or measured depth. Time and depth graphs have two axes. The primary axis is the graph index, either time or the measured depth of the well. The data in every track is plotted against the data for the graph index. In vertical graphs, the graph index is on the right side of the..."},"87":{y:0,u:"../Content/App_Shell/Dashboards/DASH_Graphs_Depth_Customize.htm",l:-1,t:"Customizing depth graphs",i:0.00424748485710499,a:"Time and depth graphs plot curve data against either time or measured depth. Time and depth graphs have two axes. The primary axis is the graph index, either time or the measured depth of the well. The data in every track is plotted against the data for the graph index. In vertical graphs, the graph index is on the right side of the..."},"88":{y:0,u:"../Content/Projects/PROJ_AllProjects_About.htm",l:-1,t:"All Projects",i:0.00151190120380298,a:"In the Drilling Engineering Software application suite, all of the data related to a job is stored with the well. Wells are managed from the Projects screen in Drilling Engineering Software. On the Projects screen, you can manage projects, create new projects, import well objects into the current well, import well configurations, and export data."},"89":{y:0,u:"../Content/Projects/PROJ_AllProjects_Projects.htm",l:-1,t:"Managing Projects",i:0.0112448780617351,a:"All of the data related to a job is stored with a project. This includes job information, the rig configuration, well data, fluid properties, limits and alarms,  settings, and other data. On the Projects \u003e All Projects \u003e Projects page, you can create a new well, change the active well, switch between modes, and delete inactive wells. The active well is marked by a ..."},"90":{y:0,u:"../Content/Projects/PROJ_AllProjects_ImportProj.htm",l:-1,t:"Project imports",i:0.00843474909807145,a:"Drilling Engineering Software project files are compressed files that can contain different types of data, such as dashboards, drillstrings, tool catalogs, custom connections, and well configurations. On the File \u003e Import Project page, you can import a well into Drilling Engineering Software. Importing Drilling Engineering Software projects allows you to easily collaborate..."},"91":{y:0,u:"../Content/Projects/PROJ_AllProjects_Export.htm",l:-1,t:"Exports",i:0.00932362622870115,a:"Exporting a well creates a compressed file with the data from the current well. You can send this file to a co-worker so they can import the file on their own machine. You can also use this feature to create a backup of your data in Drilling Engineering Software."},"92":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/MC2_Setup.htm",l:-1,t:"Setup screen",i:0.00151190120380298,a:"All of the data needed for the calculations in Drilling Engineering Software can be entered on the Setup screen. This includes surface equipment, well data, fluids, drillstrings, DAQ settings, well parameters, and other data. The pages listed below are used to enter the setup data for the well: The ..."},"93":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Surface_Equipment/RIG_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Surface equipment",i:0.00324480523703906,a:"The Setup \u003e Surface Equipment section contains information about the rig, such as the type of rig, the elevation of the rig, and the equipment on the rig. There are five basic steps for entering the rig details: Select the equipment on the rig. The equipment configuration includes the rig type and ..."},"94":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Surface_Equipment/RIG_Equip.htm",l:-1,t:"Equipment configuration",i:0.00800400832633809,a:"The Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Equipment Configuration page allows you to select the equipment on the rig, as well as the size and type of rig. The rig equipment available on the Equipment Configuration page includes blowout preventers, auxiliary pumps, and RCDs."},"95":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Surface_Equipment/RIG_Elev.htm",l:-1,t:"Rig Elevations",i:0.00895071611916029,a:"The Well View pane on the Setup \u003eSurface Equipment \u003e Equipment Configuration page shows a diagram that illustrates the kelly bushing, ground level, and water depth of the rig. The diagram shown depends on the type of rig selected in the Rig Type field."},"96":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Surface_Equipment/RIG_Pumps.htm",l:-1,t:"Pump configuration",i:0.0144974851694829,a:"The first pump is the only pump that is activated by default. If there are additional pumps on the rig, each additional pump must be activated in order to be used in Drilling Engineering Software\u0027s calculations. On the Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Piping and Instrumentation page, you can change the pump state..."},"97":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Surface_Equipment/RIG_Specs.htm",l:-1,t:"Equipment specifications",i:0.00382757023873376,a:"The Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Piping and Instrumentation page includes the equipment specifications for several types of equipment, including the mud pumps, MPD manifold, RCD, BOP, and riser. The equipment specifications are used in several calculations. You can update the specifications by selecting the equipment..."},"98":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Surface_Equipment/RIG_Schematic.htm",l:-1,t:"Rig schematic",i:0.00920173338921795,a:"The Setup \u003e Surface Equipment \u003e Piping and Instrumentation page contains a schematic of the surface equipment and piping on the rig. The equipment that appears in the rig schematic depends on the type of rig, the location of the BOP, and the equipment selected on the Equipment Configuration page."},"99":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/WD_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Well data",i:0.0012767293683753,a:"All of the data needed to describe the well can be entered on the Setup \u003e  Wells section. Before receiving data or running an analysis, you\u0027ll need to add the data listed below. Wellpath data. The real-time surveys for the well are used for all calculations. The easiest way to add survey data is to ..."},"100":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/TRJ_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Wellpath",i:0.00206877238714502,a:"The Setup \u003e Well Data \u003e Wellpath page contains the wellpath data for the planned well trajectory and real-time surveys. The drop-down menu at the top of the screen allows you to switch between the trajectory data and the survey data. The Trajectory view should be used for the survey points..."},"101":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/TRJ_SurveyPts.htm",l:-1,t:"Wellpath data",i:0.00765840929983024,a:"There are multiple ways to add trajectory and survey data on the Setup \u003e Well Data \u003e Wellpath page. If your wellpath data is in a CSV or LAS file, you can import the data from a file. If you do not have any wellpath data to import, you can also enter each survey point individually. After you have added the planned trajectory, you..."},"102":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/TRJ_Charts.htm",l:-1,t:"Trajectory charts",i:0.00852266670470163,a:"Wellpath data is plotted in several charts on the Wellpath tab. There are two types of charts available: Projection charts, which plot the projected horizontal displacement, vertical section, northing, and easting. Wellpath inspection charts, which compare the original trajectory and survey data to the corrected..."},"103":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/FRM_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Formation data",i:0.00818573952921981,a:"The Setup \u003e Well Data \u003e Formations page contains the geological and geophysical characteristics of the formation layers in the wellbore. These properties include porosity, permeability, pore pressure, and fracture pressure. Formation layers are indexed by measured depth along the length of the wellbore, from..."},"104":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/INT_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Well intervals",i:0.00248639701867353,a:"The Well Intervals page in the Setup \u003e Well Data section is used to define the geometry of the hole sections along the trajectory of the well. Casing sections are listed in the top portion of the Well Intervals page, and open hole sections are listed at the bottom. The Well View pane shows a preview of the..."},"105":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/INT_WB.htm",l:-1,t:"Wellbores",i:0.00191675188810367,a:"In Drilling Engineering Software, you can create multiple wellbores. While a well is in the planning stages, the planned wellbore geometry may change several times. When this happens, you can create a new wellbore with the updated geometry. This allows you to run analyses on different wellbores, as well as keep an archive..."},"106":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/INT_OH.htm",l:-1,t:"Open hole sections",i:0.00506501978530715,a:"Open hole sections are listed in the bottom portion of the Well Intervals page, and casing sections are listed at the top. Open hole sections are also listed in order, from the surface of the well to the bottom of the well. The top of the first open hole section is determined automatically, based on the rig elevations on the Surface..."},"107":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Well_Data/INT_Casing.htm",l:-1,t:"Casing and liner sections",i:0.00314734948612245,a:"Casing and liner sections are listed in the top portion of the Well Intervals page. There are three basic types of casing sections in Drilling Engineering Software: casing, tapered casing, and liner. Casing is cemented in place and extends to the surface. Tapered casing is a casing section with multiple casing sizes, such as..."},"108":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Fluids/FLD_Mud_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Drilling muds",i:0.0124372041544899,a:"Muds, also known as drilling fluids, are used to maintain pressure in the wellbore and clean cuttings away from the bit during drilling operations. There are four types of muds in Drilling Engineering Software: water-based muds, oil-based muds, synthetic-based muds, and mineral oil-based muds."},"109":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Fluids/FLD_Mud_Basic.htm",l:-1,t:"Basic mud properties",i:0.0138864350256151,a:"When you create a new mud, the basic fluid properties are entered in the left side of the screen. The basic fluid properties listed in the Parameters section include mud type, mud weight, temperatures, and the fluid composition. If the mud report includes additional information, such as salt type and salinity, you can enter this information in the Advanced Properties ..."},"110":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Fluids/FLD_Mud_Rheo.htm",l:-1,t:"Rheological properties",i:0.00317691357362554,a:"Rheology can be calculated from dial readings or rheological properties, such as plastic viscosity and yield point. There are three ways to define the rheology of a mud. Dial Readings. This method uses viscometer readings to define rheological properties. You can use this method for any mud. PV YP LSYP. This method is best for Bingham plastic fluids ..."},"111":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Fluids/FLD_Mud_Dial.htm",l:-1,t:"Dial readings",i:0.00187268950636058,a:"The Dial Readings tab uses readings directly from a viscometer to calculate the rheological properties of a fluid. Dial readings can be used to define the rheology of any mud, without calculating additional values such as PV or YP. The rheological properties of the mud are calculated using one dial reading for the fluid. Viscometer..."},"112":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Fluids/FLD_Mud_PVYP.htm",l:-1,t:"PV YP LSYP properties",i:0.00233407919513032,a:"The PV YP LSYP tab allows you to enter the rheological properties for a Bingham plastic mud. Bingham plastic muds are fluids that require a minimum shear stress to start and maintain flow. There are two primary parameters for the Bingham plastic rheology model: plastic viscosity and yield point. Plastic viscosity and yield point..."},"113":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Fluids/FLD_Mud_HB.htm",l:-1,t:"H-B Direct properties",i:0.00233407919513032,a:"The H-B Direct tab uses parameters from the Herschel-Bulkley rheology model to calculate the rheological properties of muds. The Herschel-Bulkey model can be used for Bingham plastic fluids, as well as Power law fluids. The Herschel-Bulkley model uses three parameters: The Power law exponent, which is..."},"114":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Fluids/FLD_Mud_DialPVT.htm",l:-1,t:"PVT dial readings",i:0.00148261863681407,a:"The Dial Readings (PVT) tab uses dial readings taken at multiple temperatures to calculate the rheological properties of a fluid. Dial readings can be used to define the rheology of any mud, without calculating additional values such as PV or YP. Viscometer readings are used to calculate the \u0027s plastic viscosity, yield point..."},"115":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Fluids/FLD_Mud_TempRheo.htm",l:-1,t:"Temperature dependent rheology",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"In this article About temperature dependent rheology Entering rheology data Field definitions About temperature dependent rheology The Temperature Dependent Rheology tab uses the mud type, weight, and temperature to automatically calculate the dial readings for the mud. The calculated dial readings ..."},"116":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Work_String/WS_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Work strings",i:0.00223615831565202,a:"The Setup \u003e Work String page is used to build the work strings used while drilling and casing a well. Drilling Engineering Software includes the Weatherford catalog, which is the master catalog for BHA and drillstring components. It contains many of the tools manufactured by Weatherford, such as RSS units, mud motors, and LWD/MWD tools. "},"117":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Work_String/WS_Parts.htm",l:-1,t:"Work string components",i:0.00196570534809536,a:"In Drilling Engineering Software, the Weatherford catalog contains several types of work string components. For more information about customizing specific tools, refer to the topics below. Adjustable Gauge Stabilizers. Adjustable gauge stabilizers are used above the drilling motor to make changes to the build rate and rotary build rate characteristics of the ..."},"118":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Work_String/WS_Parts_Bit.htm",l:-1,t:"Drill bits",i:0.00404559905538267,a:"Most drill bits are divided into three basic part sections: the fish neck, the gauge, and the bit face. The Drilling Engineering Software catalog contains several types of drill bits, including PDC, roller cone, mill tooth, and hybrid bits. The drill bit must be the last component listed, so it should always be the first component added..."},"119":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Work_String/WS_Parts_DrillCollar.htm",l:-1,t:"Drill collars",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"Drill collars are thick, heavy-walled tubes used between the bit and the drill pipe to provide a pendulum effect for the drillstring and add weight to the bit. In Drilling Engineering Software, drill collars are composed of one uniform pipe section for the body of the drill collar. Uniform pipe sections have the same OD, ID, and nominal weight across the length of the section."},"120":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Work_String/WS_Parts_DrillPipe.htm",l:-1,t:"Drill pipes",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"Drill pipes are composed of three uniform pipe sections: the top connection, the body, and the bottom connection. Each uniform section has the same OD, ID, and nominal weight across the length of the section. In a drillstring, drill pipe is the primary drillstring component from the top of the BHA to the top of the well. Drilling Engineering Software automatically replicates the last component ..."},"121":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Work_String/WS_Parts_HWDP.htm",l:-1,t:"HWDPs",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"Heavyweight drill pipe is drill pipe that has thicker walls and longer tool joints, as well as a wear pad in the middle. HWDP is used between the bit and the drill pipe to reduce the chances of drill pipe fatigue or failure. In Drilling Engineering Software, HWDP is composed of six uniform part sections: the top connection, the body, the elevator upset, the central upset, the bottom upset ..."},"122":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Work_String/WS_Parts_Stab.htm",l:-1,t:"Stabilizers",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"Stabilizers are used to keep the drillstring centered in the wellbore and are located throughout the drillstring. They can be located near the drill bit, or along the length of the drillstring. Stabilizers are defined by their nominal size, blade count, and total mass, as well as the dimensions of each part section."},"123":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Work_String/WS_Parts_Sub.htm",l:-1,t:"Subs",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"The Drilling Engineering Software catalog contains several types of rotary subs and circulation subs, including: Crossover subs, which are used to connect drillstring parts with different connections or sizes.Bit subs, which are located directly above the drill bit. Saver subs, which are used to absorb connection wear between the drillstring and the top drive, or between ..."},"124":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/DAQ/DAQ_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Data acquisition",i:0.00142920989073354,a:"In the Setup \u003e DAQ section, you can configure the settings for sending and receiving data from different types of data sources. On the WITS page, you can configure the WITS records and items sent and received by Drilling Engineering Software.  See \"WITS data\". On the WITSML page, you can configure ..."},"125":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/DAQ/DAQ_WITS_About.htm",l:-1,t:"WITS data",i:0.00864928845174243,a:"WITS is a two-way communication system used for sending and receiving drilling data. WITS data can be sent across the network through a TCP/IP connection. The Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITS page is used to configure Drilling Engineering Software to send and receive WITS data."},"126":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/DAQ/DAQ_WITS_Channels.htm",l:-1,t:"WITS channels",i:0.00938374164804951,a:"The Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITS \u003e Channels tab lists the incoming and outgoing WITS channels. This list tells Drilling Engineering Software the IP address and port number to use for sending and receiving WITS data. Before Drilling Engineering Software can send or receive WITS data, you\u0027ll need to add incoming and..."},"127":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/DAQ/DAQ_WITS_In.htm",l:-1,t:"Incoming WITS records",i:0.00361855361560594,a:"The Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITS \u003e In tab lists the incoming WITS mnemonics that will be received by Drilling Engineering Software. This list tells Drilling Engineering Software what WITS data to look for and where to look for it. Any incoming WITS data that is not listed on the DAQ \u003e WITS \u003e In tab will be ignored by Drilling Engineering Software."},"128":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/DAQ/DAQ_WITS_Out.htm",l:-1,t:"Outgoing WITS records",i:0.00210330540112535,a:"The Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITS \u003e Out tab lists the outgoing WITS mnemonics that will be sent from Drilling Engineering Software. This list tells Drilling Engineering Software what data to send and where to send it. Before can send any WITS data, you\u0027ll need to add entries for all outgoing WITS data."},"129":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/DAQ/DAQ_WML_About.htm",l:-1,t:"WITSML channels",i:0.0274938970223289,a:"WITSML is the petroleum industry\u0027s standard for sharing drilling and completions data. Using WITSML allows you to easily send and receive real-time data, without worrying about incompatible data formats and software.The Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITSML page is used to configure Drilling Engineering Software to receive WITSML data."},"130":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/DAQ/DAQ_WML_Out.htm",l:-1,t:"WITSML Out",i:0.00237609268883654,a:"On the Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITSML Out page, you can send calculated values from Drilling Engineering Software to one of the logs on the WITSML server. Drilling Engineering Software does not automatically create or configure any logs for outgoing WITSML data. However, after the appropriate logs have been created..."},"131":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Mappings/MAP_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Mappings",i:0.0012767293683753,a:"In the Setup \u003e Mappings section, you can configure the parameters used by Drilling Engineering Software. There are two sets of parameters on the Mappings page: Well parameters such as bit depth, well depth, ROP, and hookload can be mapped on the Parameters tab. These parameters are essential for..."},"132":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Mappings/MAP_Params.htm",l:-1,t:"Parameters",i:0.0154247766998596,a:"Well parameters such as bit depth, well depth, ROP, and hookload are used by Drilling Engineering Software to create persistent curves for graphs and gauges. If you lose connection with the WITS or WITSML server, gauges and graphs that are mapped to well parameter curves will remain intact."},"133":{y:0,u:"../Content/Setup/Mappings/MAP_ActCode.htm",l:-1,t:"WITSML activity codes",i:0.00162487344766287,a:"If your WITSML data includes rig activity codes, you can configure the way Drilling Engineering Software handles the incoming activity data on the Setup \u003e Mappings \u003e WITSML Activity Code page. An activity code indicates which rig activity is currently being performed on the rig. Drilling Engineering Software includes..."},"134":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PLAN_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Planning screen",i:0.00188231320430102,a:"The  Planning screen contains several types of analysis, as well as calculation tools that allow you to perform quick calculations, but only require a minimum amount of input. There are four sections on the  Planning screen. The Mechanics section contains analysis tools for drillstring analysis, ..."},"135":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Calc/PLAN_Calc_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Calculation tools",i:0.00146253520366666,a:"The following calculation tools are available on the  Planning \u003e Calculators section. The Kill Sheet tool calculates the kill parameters required to shut in the well during an influx.  See \"Kill sheet tool\". The Stuck Pipe tool calculates the most likely cause for a stuck pipe.  See \"Stuck pipe ..."},"136":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Calc/PLAN_Calc_KillSheet.htm",l:-1,t:"Kill sheet tool",i:0.00256857688160314,a:"The kill sheet tool on the Planning \u003e Calculators \u003e Kill Sheet page allows you to calculate the kill parameters required to shut in the well during an influx. The kill parameters calculated include stroke counts, recommended kill mud weight, and circulating pressures."},"137":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Calc/PLAN_Calc_StuckPipe.htm",l:-1,t:"Stuck pipe calculator",i:0.00256857688160314,a:"The stuck pipe calculator on the Planning \u003e Calculators \u003e Stuck Pipe page calculates the most likely cause for a stuck pipe, which helps you determine the best approach to freeing the stuck pipe. The stuck pipe calculator examines the real-time data received immediately before and after the stuck pipe event. It uses the real-time data to answer four questions: What was ..."},"138":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Calc/PLAN_Calc_Bit.htm",l:-1,t:"Bit configuration tool",i:0.0044599851693571,a:"The bit configuration tool on the Planning \u003e Calculators \u003e Bit page can be used to determine the best nozzle configuration for the drill bit. The bit configuration tool calculates bit pressure loss and hydraulic horsepower, based on the flow rate, mud weight, and nozzle configuration."},"139":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_AP_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Geomechanics",i:0.00205081523216686,a:"Geomechanics analysis examines the forces acting on the wellbore formation and the formation fluids. Geomechanics results are calculated using the formation data entered in the Setup screen, as well as data from an offset well and real-time data. Each experiment on the Planning \u003e Geomechanics page is divided into three tabs...\r\n"},"140":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APL_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Lithology analysis",i:0.00190265770965061,a:"The Lithology tab identifies the locations of shale and clay formations, using imported log data and the shale formation layers defined in the Setup screen. On the Lithology tab, you can import log data for ROP, gamma ray, and spontaneous potential."},"141":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APL_DeliverLine.htm",l:-1,t:"Deliver lines",i:0.0097777879438157,a:"On the Lithology tab, the Deliver Line tool allows you to manually define shale areas. Deliver lines are used to set the minimum ROP and gamma ray values found in shale formation layers, creating a threshold that separates shale areas from the rest of the formation. The log values in a shale area should exceed this threshold, while the log values in other formation layers should be below the threshold."},"142":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APL_BoundaryAreas.htm",l:-1,t:"Boundary areas",i:0.0097777879438157,a:"On the Lithology tab, the Bound tool allows you to add boundaries that represent depths of interest for the analysis. If there are no boundary areas defined, then the Results chart will show the results for all depths. You can add boundary areas to the Well Data, Offset Well, and Current Well charts."},"143":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APO_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Overburden analysis",i:0.00180523212537871,a:"The Overburden tab examines the pressure exerted by the weight of the overlying sediments in the formation, using imported log data and the formation density data defined in the Setup screen. On the Overburden tab, you can import density, sonic, seismic, and check shot data."},"144":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APO_DensityTrend.htm",l:-1,t:"Density trend lines",i:0.00912839741123224,a:"On the Overburden tab, the Extrapolation tool allows you to add a trend line that shows the density trend as the well gets deeper. The density trend line is used to calculate the overburden and hydrostatic pressure values in the Results chart. Density trend lines are extrapolated from three points: the mud line, an upper boundary..."},"145":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APO_BoundaryAreas.htm",l:-1,t:"Boundary areas",i:0.00912839741123224,a:"On the Overburden tab, the Bound tool allows you to add boundaries that represent depths of interest for the analysis. If there are no boundary areas defined, then the Results chart will show the results for all depths. You can add boundary areas to the Well Data, Offset Well, and Current Well charts."},"146":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APO_CalcSettings.htm",l:-1,t:"Overburden calculation settings",i:0.00912839741123224,a:"On the Overburden tab, you can change the settings for some of the overburden calculations. This includes the coefficients for the Gardner method, which is used to calculate the formation density from logs for seismic, sonic, and check shot data. You can also change the density of the formation fluid, as well as the settings for..."},"147":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APP_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Pore pressure analysis",i:0.00190265770965061,a:"The Pore Pressure tab analyzes the pressure acting on the formation fluids, using imported log data and the calculated shale and clay layers from the Lithology tab. On the Pore Pressure tab, you can import log data for drilling exponent (DXC), resistivity, sonic, and neutron porosity data."},"148":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APP_NormalizeTrend.htm",l:-1,t:"Trend lines",i:0.0097777879438157,a:"On the Pore Pressure tab, the Linear Trend Line and Semi-Log Trend Line tools allow you to add a trend line to normalize your log data. The normalized trend line is used as a baseline to calculate pore pressure by comparing the filtered log values against the hydrostatic gradient. Linear trend lines are defined by the slope of the line..."},"149":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/PP/PLAN_APP_CalcSettings.htm",l:-1,t:"Pore pressure calculation settings",i:0.0097777879438157,a:"On the Pore Pressure tab, you can change the coefficients used for some of the pore pressure calculations. This includes the Eaton Resistivity method, which is used to estimate pore pressure from log data for resistivity. It also includes the Eaton Transient Time method for converting sonic data into pore pressure, as well as..."},"150":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/PLAN_AH_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Hydraulics analysis",i:0.00293243783618995,a:"Hydraulics analysis examines the pressure losses in the circulating system so that you can optimize the hydraulics in the well. There are several types of hydraulics analyses available, including snapshot analysis, parametric analysis, bit hydraulics optimization, swab and surge analysis, displacement analysis, influx simulation..."},"151":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Snapshot/PLAN_AHS_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Snapshot analysis",i:0.0043944400167393,a:"A snapshot analysis gives you a quick summary of the fluid\u0027s predicted behavior in the wellbore, based on a single value for each operating parameter. It calculates several depth profiles that predict how the fluid properties and wellbore pressures will change throughout the well."},"152":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Snapshot/PLAN_AHS_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Snapshot analysis settings",i:0.00184790332949025,a:"When you run a snapshot analysis, there are two models available for hole cleaning: The Basic hole cleaning model uses probability distribution functions to estimate downhole cleaning conditions under varying operating parameters. The primary outputs of the basic hole cleaning model are cuttings concentration, bed height..."},"153":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Snapshot/PLAN_AHS_Results_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Snapshot results",i:0.00397987473423926,a:"The results of a snapshot analysis provide you with several depth profiles, which give you a quick summary of a fluid\u0027s predicted behavior in the wellbore. Using these results, you can see how the fluid properties and wellbore pressures will change throughout the well."},"154":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Snapshot/PLAN_AHS_Results_Summary.htm",l:-1,t:"Snapshot results summary",i:0.0160748476794174,a:"The results summary for a snapshot hydraulics analysis includes a summary of pressure distribution, a summary of the pressures and temperatures affecting the configurable components, a detailed depth profile, and well inteval calculations."},"155":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Snapshot/PLAN_AHS_Results_Full.htm",l:-1,t:"Detailed snapshot analysis results",i:0.0170624226463929,a:"The results summary for a snapshot hydraulics analysis includes a summary of pressure distribution, a summary of the pressures and temperatures affecting the configurable components, a detailed depth profile, and well inteval calculations."},"156":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Snapshot/PLAN_AHS_Results_Charts.htm",l:-1,t:"Snapshot charts",i:0.0108399507796977,a:"After you run a snapshot hydraulics analysis, you can view the analysis charts in the Charts view. These charts include depth profiles for inclination, rheology, ECD, fluid velocity, temperature, hole cleaning, cuttings transport ratio, and pressure."},"157":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/BitHyd/PLAN_AHB_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Bit hydraulics optimization",i:0.00271490041685636,a:"Bit hydraulics optimization determines the optimal flow rate, which maximizes ROP while ensuring that the drilling margin and good hole cleaning are maintained. This analysis examines the pump configuration to determine if it can provide the necessary flow rate. It also provides guidance for selecting the best bit nozzle sizes."},"158":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/BitHyd/PLAN_AHB_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Bit hydraulics optimization settings",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"The results for bit hydraulics optimization are influenced by factors such as pump pressure, ROP, annular velocity, bit TFA, the number of nozzles on the bit, top drive speed, the size and density of the cuttings, and the inlet temperature of the fluid."},"159":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/BitHyd/PLAN_AHB_Results_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Bit hydraulics results",i:0.00309263172347579,a:"Bit hydraulics optimization provides you with flow rate profiles for jet impact force, parasitic loss, hydraulic horsepower at the pump, and hydraulic horsepower at the bit. Using these results can help you determine the best flow rate and nozzle sizes to improve ROP."},"160":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/BitHyd/PLAN_AHB_Results_Summary.htm",l:-1,t:"Bit hydraulics optimization summary",i:0.00193879241717641,a:"The results summary for bit hydraulics optimization includes three types of results: the minimum and maximum recommended flow rate, the optimization parameters for bit hydraulic horsepower, and the optimization parameters for jet impact force."},"161":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/BitHyd/PLAN_AHB_Results_Charts.htm",l:-1,t:"Bit hydraulics charts",i:0.0129227128202324,a:"After you run a bit hydraulics optimization analysis, you can view the analysis chart in the Charts view. The analysis chart shows the effects of flow rate on hydraulic horsepower and impact force. Force is plotted on the left axis, and horsepower is plotted on the right axis."},"162":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Tripping/PLAN_AHT_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Surge and swab analysis",i:0.00271490041685636,a:"Swab and surge analysis predicts the swab and surge effects on pressure when running the bit in or out of the well, for open or closed systems. You can also use the analysis to calculate an optimal running speed profile that does not violate the thresholds for pore pressure or fracture pressure."},"163":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Tripping/PLAN_AHT_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Swab and surge analysis settings",i:0.00708280022920996,a:"Swab and surge pressures are affected by many factors, including the fluid\u0027s rheological properties, the running speed and acceleration at which the pipe enters or exits the well, the dimensions of the annulus, and the length of the drillstring in the well."},"164":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Tripping/PLAN_AHT_Results_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Swab and surge analysis results",i:0.00267034197027915,a:"Swab and surge analysis provides you with several depth profiles, such as fluid rheology, pipe velocity, bottomhole gauge, and bit gauge. Using these results can help you avoid pressure changes that impair the stability of the wellbore."},"165":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Tripping/PLAN_AHT_Results_Summary.htm",l:-1,t:"Swab and surge results summary",i:0.00151650266397977,a:"The results summary for a swab and surge analysis includes a profile of the predicted trip, which appears in the data table at the bottom of the screen. Each time a stand of pipe enters or exits the wellbore, the analysis calculates values for speed, acceleration, and ECD."},"166":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Tripping/PLAN_AHT_Results_Charts.htm",l:-1,t:"Swab and surge charts",i:0.0101083289630203,a:"After you run a swab and surge analysis, you can view the analysis charts in the Charts view. These charts include depth profiles for inclination, rheology, max speed, ECD at total depth, ECD at the casing shoe, ECD at the reference depth, and ECD at the end of the work string."},"167":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Displacement/PLAN_AHD_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Displacement analysis",i:0.010404557093167,a:"On the Tools \u003e Hydraulics \u003e Displacement page, you can run a displacement analysis. A displacement analysis simulates the movement of fluids through the wellbore during drilling or cementing operations. You can create a fluid train with multiple fluids, such as cements, spacers, and muds."},"168":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Displacement/PLAN_AHD_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Displacement settings",i:0.0013492609620073,a:"When you run a displacement analysis, you can simulate the displacement that occurs when pumping in a new fluid or when circulating fluids through the well. Pumping and circulation simulations can either be volume-based or time-based. Volume-based operations simulate displacement based on the volume of fluid to be pumped..."},"169":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Displacement/PLAN_AHD_Config_Depth.htm",l:-1,t:"Depth-based displacement operations",i:0.00899397998494418,a:"In this article About depth-based operations Adding a depth-based operation Field definitions About depth-based operations Depth-based operations simulate displacement based on the top depth of the fluid column when you start pumping or circulation. The simulation calculates the volume required to ..."},"170":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Displacement/PLAN_AHD_Config_Time.htm",l:-1,t:"Time-based displacement operations",i:0.00899397998494418,a:"In this article About time-based operations Adding time-based operations Field definitions About time-based operations Time-based operations simulate displacement based on the length of time that you will be pumping or circulating. The simulation calculates the volume of fluid that will be pumped or ..."},"171":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Displacement/PLAN_AHD_Config_Volume.htm",l:-1,t:"Volume-based displacement operations",i:0.00899397998494418,a:"In this article About volume-based operations Adding a volume-based operation Field definitions About volume-based operations Volume-based operations simulate displacement based on the fluid volume. The simulation calculates the time required to pump or circulate the specified volume of fluid, based ..."},"172":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Displacement/PLAN_AHD_Results_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Displacement results",i:0.00148261863681407,a:"Displacement analysis provides you with time-based profiles for the displacement of the different fluids in the fluid train. Using these results, you can see how the fluid train impacts flow rates, pressures, ECD, and free fall throughout the displacement."},"173":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Displacement/PLAN_AHD_Results_Summary.htm",l:-1,t:"Displacement summary",i:0.00148261863681407,a:"The results summary for a displacement analysis includes a schedule of the operations included in the analysis. Each row in the table is color-coded according to the operation that is in progress at that point in the displacement. For example, values calculated during the first operation will have a red marker at the beginning..."},"174":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Hyd/Displacement/PLAN_AHD_Results_Charts.htm",l:-1,t:"Displacement charts",i:0.00988289102540791,a:"After you run a displacement analysis, you can view the analysis charts in the Charts view. These charts include depth profiles for flow rate changes, standpipe pressure, and ECD. The Show Graphs button will appear in the top toolbar. This button is used to switch between the main view, which contains the analysis settings and the results summary, and the Charts view..."},"175":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/PLAN_AM_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Mechanics analyses",i:0.00293243783618995,a:"Mechanics analysis examines the effects of various forces on the BHA, as well as the effects of friction on the drillstring. This analysis is useful for selecting the best BHA and drillstring, as well as for identifying potential problems with a particular BHA configuration."},"176":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/TnD/PLAN_AMTD_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Torque and drag analysis",i:0.00330419912362333,a:"On the Planning \u003e Mechanics \u003e Torque and Drag (T\u0026D) page, you can run a torque and drag analysis. Torque and drag analysis predicts the torque \u0026 drag forces generated by the drillstring during various wellbore operations. It calculates the forces, torques, and stresses that act on the drillstring at the specified bit depth."},"177":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/TnD/PLAN_AMTD_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Torque and drag settings",i:0.00148261863681407,a:"To run a torque and drag analysis, go to the Planning \u003e Mechanics \u003e Torque and Drag (T\u0026D) page. The operations available for torque and drag analysis include drilling, sliding, tripping in and out, rotating off-bottom, reaming, and backreaming."},"178":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/TnD/PLAN_AMTD_Results_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Torque and drag results",i:0.00344210141230585,a:"Torque and drag analysis results examine the effects of forces, torques, and other stresses on the drillstring during various drilling operations. Using these results, you can analyze the hole conditions that will occur during drilling and choose the best operating parameters for the well."},"179":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/TnD/PLAN_AMTD_Results_Summary.htm",l:-1,t:"Torque \u0026 drag results summary",i:0.0163827352099801,a:"The results summary for torque and drag analysis includes maximum predicted values and a summary of each operation. If the work string includes wireline tools or cable, the results summary also includes warning messages related to the wireline tools and cable. The maximum predicted values are shown in the Maximum Values section of the results summary ..."},"180":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/TnD/PLAN_AMTD_Results_Charts.htm",l:-1,t:"Torque and drag charts",i:0.0163827352099801,a:"After you run a torque and drag analysis, you can view the analysis charts in the Charts view. These charts include depth profiles for axial load, torque, contact forces, effective stress, hookload, surface torque, axial stress, torsional stress, shear stress, bending stress, and more."},"181":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Static/PLAN_AMBS_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Static BHA analysis",i:0.00271490041685636,a:"Static analysis calculates the equilibrium state of the BHA. In static analysis, the BHA is initially projected to the wellbore centerline. When the BHA is released, it begins to move due to gravity and weight on bit. This movement causes the BHA to bounce off the wellbore until it reaches an equilibrium state."},"182":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Static/PLAN_AMBS_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"Static BHA analysis settings",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"To run a BHA static analysis, go to the Tools \u003e Mechanics \u003e BHA Static page. Drilling Engineering Software calculates the forces for the defined BHA configuration, bit position, and WOB values. These forces include BHA displacement, contact forces, bending moments, and effective stresses."},"183":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Static/PLAN_AMBS_Results_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Static BHA analysis results",i:0.00439565269507285,a:"Static analysis provides you with several BHA profiles, such as BHA displacement, contact force, effective stress, and BHA clearance. There are two types of results available for static analysis: A summary of the results, which contains several critical values for each WOB value included in the analysis..."},"184":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Static/PLAN_AMBS_Results_Summary.htm",l:-1,t:"Static BHA analysis results summary",i:0.00230798624739106,a:"The results summary for a static analysis includes several critical values for each WOB included in the analysis, as well as a list of warnings for any limits that were exceeded. If the limits for contact force or Von Mises stress were exceeded during the analysis, a warning message will appear at the top of the results summary..."},"185":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Static/PLAN_AMBS_Results_Charts.htm",l:-1,t:"Static BHA analysis charts",i:0.00230798624739106,a:"After you run a BHA static analysis, you can view the analysis charts in the Charts view. These charts include depth profiles for displacement, contact forces, effective stress, axial stress, bending stress, string positions, bending moments, and clearance."},"186":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Vib/PLAN_AMBV_About.htm",l:-1,t:"BHA vibration analysis",i:0.00271490041685636,a:"Vibration analysis detects dangerous rotation speeds in the BHA, which can cause damaging downhole vibrations. Many excitations act on the BHA simultaneously during downhole operations. These excitations can include rock cutting forces, contact forces, BHA part eccentricities, and mud motor forces."},"187":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Vib/PLAN_AMBV_Config.htm",l:-1,t:"BHA vibration analysis settings",i:0.00106254231576398,a:"To run a BHA vibration anlaysis, go to the Planning \u003e Mechanics \u003e BHA Vibration page. Vibration analysis calculates the resulting forces for the defined BHA configuration, bit positions, WOB values, and top drive speeds. These forces include vibrations, critical speeds, contact forces, and effective stresses."},"188":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Vib/PLAN_AMBV_Results_About.htm",l:-1,t:"BHA vibration analysis results",i:0.00281445660634488,a:"Vibration analysis provides you with several BHA profiles, such as lateral and axial vibrations, critical speeds, BHA displacement, contact force, and effective stress. There are three types of results available for vibration analysis: a summary of the results, analysis charts, and critical speed maps."},"189":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Vib/PLAN_AMBV_Results_Summary.htm",l:-1,t:"BHA vibration analysis results summary",i:0.0016606173000455,a:"The results summary for vibration analysis includes critical speed maps and a table of the calculated maximum amplitudes, as well as a list of warnings for any limits that were exceeded. If the limits for contact force or Von Mises stress were exceeded during the analysis, a warning message will appear at the top of the results..."},"190":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Vib/PLAN_AMBV_Results_Charts.htm",l:-1,t:"BHA vibration charts",i:0.0110688003289352,a:"After you run a BHA vibration analysis, you can view the analysis charts in the Charts view. These charts include depth profiles for lateral vibrations, axial vibrations, torsional vibrations, displacement, contact forces, axial stress, bending stress, string positions, clearance, and more."},"191":{y:0,u:"../Content/Plan/Mech/BHA_Vib/PLAN_AMBV_Results_CritSpeed.htm",l:-1,t:"Critical speed maps",i:0.0016606173000455,a:"After you run a BHA vibration analysis, you can view the critical speed maps in the Charts view. These charts include show the lateral combinations generated during rotary drilling and slide drilling, for every combination of WOB and top drive speed included in the analysis."},"192":{y:0,u:"../Content/Alarms/ALRM_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Alarms",i:0.00131170296886336,a:"The Alarms screen allows you to set alarm limits, view active alarms, and view a historical log of the alarms triggered. The Set Limits section contains the alarm settings for calculated values, WITS data, WITSML data, and parameters.  See \"Set Limits\". The Active page lists the status of all active ..."},"193":{y:0,u:"../Content/Alarms/ALRM_SetLimits_About.htm",l:-1,t:"Set Limits",i:0.0162942536672905,a:"The Alarms \u003e Set Limits section contains the limits for different types of alarms, such as alarms for incoming data, calculations, and well parameters. The Hydraulics page contains alarm limits for some of values calculated by the hydraulics model. The Parameters page contains alarm limits for the well parameters on the Setup \u003e Mappings \u003e Parameters page. The ..."},"194":{y:0,u:"../Content/Alarms/ALRM_SetLimits_Params.htm",l:-1,t:"Well parameter alarms",i:0.00486685339185257,a:"The Alarms \u003e Set Limits \u003e Parameters page contains the alarm limits for well parameters defined on the Setup \u003e Mappings \u003e Parameters page. Values outside of the Minimum and Maximum range are considered invalid, even if the alarm is not enabled. When Drilling Engineering Software receives an invalid value for a well parameter, the mapping action selected on the ..."},"195":{y:0,u:"../Content/Alarms/ALRM_SetLimits_WITS.htm",l:-1,t:"WITS alarms",i:0.00486685339185257,a:"The Alarms \u003e Set Limits \u003e WITS page contains the alarm limits for the WITS records defined on the Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITS \u003e In tab. On the Dashboard screen, the associated curves for these alarms are listed under the Wits Data category. When an alarm is enabled, the alarm limits for the associated curve will be applied to any gauges on the Dashboard screen..."},"196":{y:0,u:"../Content/Alarms/ALRM_SetLimits_WITSML.htm",l:-1,t:"WITSML alarms",i:0.00486685339185257,a:"The Alarms \u003e Set Limits \u003e WITSML page contains the alarm limits for the WITSML data defined on the Setup \u003e DAQ \u003e WITSML tab. On the Dashboard screen, the associated curves for these alarms are listed under the name of the WITSML channel. When an alarm is enabled, the alarm limits for the associated curve will be applied to any gauges on the ..."},"197":{y:0,u:"../Content/Alarms/ALRM_Active.htm",l:-1,t:"Active alarms",i:0.0157020852727915,a:"The Active page lists the status of all active alarms triggered by exceeded limits. When an alarm limit on one of the Alarms \u003e Set Limits pages is exceeded, an alarm will be triggered and the status banner will flash yellow with an audible signal to alert you about the alarm. There are three alarm statuses on the Active page ..."},"198":{y:0,u:"../Content/Alarms/ALRM_History.htm",l:-1,t:"Alarm history",i:0.00143419278261804,a:"The Alarms \u003e History page contains a time-stamped log of all current and resolved alarms triggered by exceeded limits. When an alarm limit on one of the Alarms \u003e Set Limits pages is exceeded, an alarm will be triggered and the event will be logged on the History page. When the alarm has been resolved, a new log entry will be added."},"199":{y:0,u:"../Content/Home.htm",l:-1,t:"Help with Drilling Engineering Software",i:0.00136359665987444,a:"Whether you\u0027re new to Drilling Engineering Software or just want to learn more about Drilling Engineering Software, this guide provides the help you need. What is Drilling Engineering Software? Drilling Engineering Software allows you to plan nearly every detail of drilling a well, from the ..."},});